<b>Basellaceae</b> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../276/56276.xml">
family</link> of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../967/18967.xml">
flowering plants</link>, in the order <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../686/18947686.xml">
Caryophyllales</link> in the clade <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../053/2774053.xml">
core eudicots</link>, according to the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../671/631671.xml">
Angiosperm Phylogeny Group</link>. The family comprises some two dozen species of herbaceous plants, some with climbing habits, in four genera:</p>
<p>

<list>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../018/2410018.xml">
Anredera</link>''</it></entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../089/5350089.xml">
Basella</link>''</it></entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../472/1909472.xml">
Boussingaultia</link>''</it></entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../472/1909472.xml">
Ullucus</link>''</it></entry>
</list>
</p>
<p>

Members of economic importance include the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../666/933666.xml">
ulluco</link> and the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../199/1617199.xml">
Malabar spinach</link>.</p>

